 the PARADISO TERRESTRE -- t16 Agnes Bedford: An Invisible Helpmate -- tPART III PARIS 1921–1924 -- t17 Constantin Brâncuşi, Vorticist: Sculpture, Art Criticism, Poetry -- t18 Percussive Music for a Triangle: Ezra Pound’s Relationship with George Antheil and Olga Rudge -- t19 ‘Like Coins out of Circulation’: Reframing Ezra Pound’s LE TESTAMENT -- t20 Ezra Pound as Music Theorist: ANTHEIL AND THE TREATISE ON HARMONY -- t21 The Expansion of a Theory: Great Bass and BALLET MÉCANIQUE -- t22 Renaissance Man: Ezra Pound’s Search for a Contemporary Colour Palette Through His Solo Violin Works -- tPART IV THE ITALIAN YEARS 1925–1945 -- t23 Ezra Pound’s Artistic Thinking and Relations in Italy, 1925–1945 -- t24 Music Recollected: Ezra Pound’s CAVALCANTI -- t25 VIDA SIN FIN: Ezra Pound and Gerhart Münch -- tPART V WASHINGTON: MENTORING THE YOUNG IN THE 1950s -- t26 Sheri Martinelli: The White Goddess -- t27 Art ‘in the Solid’: Ezra Pound and Michael Lekakis -- t28 A ‘Transference of Power’: Ezra Pound and the Cinema of Hollis Frampton -- tNotes on Contributors -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShowcases Ezra Pound’s close involvement with the arts throughout his careerThe present volume of new, interdisciplinary scholarship investigates the arts with which Pound had a lifelong interaction including architecture, ballet, cinema, music, painting, photography and sculpture. Divided into 5 historically and thematically arranged sections, the 28 chapters foreground the shifting significance of art forms throughout Pound’s life which he spent in London, Paris, Rapallo and Washington.The Companion maps Pound’s practices of engagement with the arts, deepening areas of study that have recently emerged, such as his musical compositions. At the same time, it opens up new fields, particularly Pound’s interaction with the performing arts: opera, dance, and cinema. The volume demonstrates overall that Ezra Pound was no mere spectator of the modernist revolution in the arts; rather he was an agent of change, a doer and promoter who also had a deep emotional response to the arts.Key Features:The first book to gather together all the different aspects of the subject of Pound and the artsChapters are devoted to topics never covered before: (cinema; political anarchism; early music; Agnes Bedford; the artists Munch, Lekakis, Martinelli, Frampton) Presents the ways Pound’s interests and activities in the arts change over time in a continuous story, from his beginnings to his old ageIncludes portraits of friendships and short biographies of artists connected to Pound, showing his personal impact in the arts world  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aModernism (Art). 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntliff, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBacigalupo, Massimo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrantley Berryman, Jo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByron, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz Cornejo, Heriberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemetriou, Galateia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunton, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElder, R. Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerreccio, Giuliana, econtribu